{"add":{"doc":{"id":"67bcef58a75b517e6905198d3cbee1c59eca2a4ec3058fe099af5e4879abf843","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Wiccan_spouses.PNG/200px-Wiccan_spouses.PNG","previous":[],"after":["Handfasting is the commonly used term for Wiccan weddings. Some Wiccans observe the practice of a trial marriage for a year and a day, which some traditions hold should be contracted on the Sabbat of Lughnasadh, as this was the traditional time for trial, \"Telltown marriages\" among the Irish. A common marriage vow in Wicca is \"for as long as love lasts\" instead of the traditional Christian \"till death do us part\". The first ever known Wiccan wedding ceremony took part in 1960 amongst the Bricket Wood coven, between Frederic Lamond and his first wife, Gillian."]}}}